commitResults.messageTitle: Resolve issued affecting the correctness of the unit tests in EditMeetingCommandTest.
commitResults.messageBody:
Previously, the constructor for a new Meeting needs to take in the date and time in
unprocessed format.
Therefore, the previous iterations of the code had to depend heavily on converting
the date and time format between dd-MM-yyyy HHmm and EEEE, dd MMMM yyyy hh:mm a,
such as through the method getNonProcessedDateAndTime()

However, after moving the processing of date and time forward to the parser
when creating a new meeting, all date and time format in calling the constructor
of Meeting will be in dd MMMM yyyy hh:mm a format, effectivrly bypassing
getNonProcessedDateAndTime(). I hope this will make the code and dateTime
format conversion less complicated.

Now, the EditMeetingCommandParser also validates the date and time inputted
by the user and converts it to EEEE, dd MMMM yyyy hh:mm a format
which will be used to replace the existing date and time of the
meeting to be edited.

Resolve issues that result in Unit tests failing in EditMeetingCommandParserTest.java
commitResults.messageBody:
The raw input of the user for date and time should be in dd-MM-yyyy format,
whereas EditMeetingCommandParser::parse will convert the format of the date and time
to EEEE, dd MMMM yyyy hh:mm a format.

Thus, the EditMeetingDescriptionBuilder will take in a simulated raw user input
BUT the date and time needs to be converted to EEEE, dd MMMM yyyy hh:mm a format,
before the descriptor is passed into the constructor for EditMeetingCommand

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix bug resulting in auto rounding of the last day of month when creating a new meeting.
commitResults.messageBody:
Previously, when the user input for the meeting date is 31-04-2000,
the resulted date stored will be 30 April 2000, as the programme
automatically rounds down the date to the closest validate date
(i.e. to the closest last day of the month)

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix bug that affects equality check of the list of Persons to meet.
commitResults.messageBody:
Previously when two meetings are created with the same person in different input order,
the code will consider both meetings as different. This is due to the ObservableList::equals
method only checks for equality between two lists by comparing each pair of elements
with the same index from both lists.

Hence, I have implemented a quick fix to sort both lists before comparison in ::equals.

commitResults.messageTitle: Apply the same fix from previous commit to UniqueMeetingList::equals

Reorder the validation flow of user input in CreateMeetingCommandParser::parse Previously the parser will validate the date before checking whether the number of information segments provided is correct, which sometimes results in an error message informing users of invalid date and time format when the actual problem is due to missing information.
commitResults.messageBody:
The preferred sequence of validation should be:
checking if there is missing information --> checking for empty information
--> checking if date and time format is valid

The parser will now check whether the number of information segments provided is correct,
before it proceeds to validate the date.
This reverts commit 60739f5920919700c0f04ab23c8749762e5f50d9.

commitResults.messageTitle: Reorder the validation flow of user input in CreateMeetingCommandParser::parse
commitResults.messageBody:
Previously the parser will validate the date before checking whether the
number of information segments provided is correct, which sometimes results in
an error message informing users of invalid date and time format
when the actual problem is due to missing information.

The preferred sequence of validation should be:
checking if there is missing information --> checking for empty information
--> checking if date and time format is valid

The parser will now check whether the number of information segments provided is correct,
before it proceeds to validate the date.

commitResults.messageTitle: Edit incorrect feedback message to user in the case of invalid user input for AddPersonToMeetingCommand and DeletePersonFromMeetingCommand
Fix bug where the invalid time of meeting '2400' leads to ambiguous/ unclear feedback.
Fix issue where adding two persons with similar names to a meeting results in an error.
commitResults.messageBody:
Previously the code checks for whether the name input from
the user leads to ambiguity (whether it matches more than
one person from the address book) -- if it does, an error
is thrown.

However, this results in cases where a valid full name leading
to ambiguity when there are multiple similar names. For
example, when there are contacts called 'John' and 'John Doe',
the command 'meet John ...' is expected to fetch the contact
called John, but instead an exception is thrown as both
contacts above are returned as the query result, causing
ambiguity.

The modified code divides the user input into multiple more
specific cases and is able to return the expected output
given the above case. An additional method to check for
an exact match between the user's input name and the
names of contacts is implemented.

commitResults.messageBody:
Previously when an exception is caught in CreateMeetingCommand.java,
the programme displays a CommandResult with the error message,
which refreshes the user input.

This created some inconvenience for some of our testers,
as the would like to refer to their previous user input
and modify from there, instead of typing down a new input.

Thus, in the new version, when an exception is caught,
a new CommandException containing the error message is
thrown instead, which gets caught further down and an
error message is displayed in the feedback Window,
while the original input remains in the text box (in
red font) instead of getting refreshed.
